ce:section.ce:para:
Using a three-dimensional numerical study, Huminic and Huminic [32] investigated the heat transfer performance (HTP) of a thermo-syphon HP using both NFs and water as working fluids. The primary objective was to assess the effects of varying operating temperatures and nanoparticle volume concentrations on heat transfer efficiency. The study employed γ-Fe2O3 nanoparticles dispersed in water at three different volume concentrations (0 %, 2 %, and 5.3 %) and four different operating temperatures spanning from 60 to 90 °C). The simulation results showed that increasing nanoparticle concentration greatly reduced ΔT between the evaporator and condenser. Both quantitative and qualitative analyses demonstrated that the thermo-syphon HP using NFs outperformed the conventional water-based system when evaluating heat transfer characteristics. Specifically, the evaporation heat transfer coefficient increased with higher nanoparticle concentrations (Fig. 1
                        ), and thermal resistance decreased correspondingly (Fig. 2
                        ), indicating improved overall TP.

By varying the working fluid, heat input, and angle of inclination, Kumaresan et al. [60] conducted an experimental study to examine improvements in the TP of sintered and mesh wick HPs, as illustrated in Fig. 22
                        . Both the sintered and mesh wick HPs shared the same geometric specifications: 12 mm outer diameter, 330 mm length, and 1 mm wick thickness. When charged with a nanofluid composed of 1.0 wt.% CuO in DW, the sintered and mesh wick HPs exhibited the greatest reduction in surface temperature at tilt angles of 45° and 60°, respectively. Furthermore, under identical conditions of nanoparticle concentration, heat input, and inclination angle, the sintered wick HP achieved a 13.92 % greater reduction in thermal resistance compared to the mesh wick HP (Fig. 23
                        ). The thermal conductivity of the HPs was significantly enhanced by the addition of CuO nanoparticles to DW, particularly at higher heat inputs.
